context: Codd's paper was picked up by two people at Berkeley, <a0_0><b5_0>Eugene Wong and Michael Stonebraker<b5_0/><a0_0/>. They started a project known as INGRES using funding that had already been allocated for a geographical database project and student programmers to produce code. Beginning in <a2_0><b7_0>1973<b7_0/><a2_0/>, <a1_0><b6_0>INGRES<b6_0/><a1_0/> delivered its first test products which were generally ready for widespread use in <b9_0>1979<b9_0/>. INGRES was similar to System R in a number of ways, including the use of a "language" for data access, known as <a3_0><b8_0>QUEL<b8_0/><a3_0/>. Over time, <a4_0>INGRES moved to the emerging SQL standard<a4_0/>.
